  &lt;p&gt;I&#39;m not very good with IPA vowels, but I&#39;m pretty confident Ah is
supposed to be the a in father. But when I look at the template
Othermale has in the files section, my choice for ah includes palm,
lot, thought, and cloth, none of which sound like the a in father to me.&lt;br&gt;
  &lt;br&gt;
I think for palm I&#39;m the victim of assimilation; my dialect has
absorbed the &#39;lm&#39; so thoroughly into the preceding vowel that it&#39;s
stuck there forever, I&#39;ve yet to find a word with that same vowel that
wasn&#39;t in the &quot;alm&quot; context. You might convince me that palm is just
AWE+m, but...&lt;br&gt;
  &lt;br&gt;
If I say them together long enough, I can make lot and father come out
close enough that I can pretend I&#39;m imagining the difference, but I can
do the same thing for lot and cloth, and then do the same thing again
for cloth and thaw, and I *cannot* do the same thing for thaw and
father.&lt;br&gt;
  &lt;br&gt;
I can travel in a similar direction towards thought, so I end up with a
triangle, father-thought-&lt;wbr&gt;thaw, or minimally paired, pause-paws.
It&#39;s tempting to think three vowels, three letters, but if Ah is father
and Awe is thaw, then thought would have to be ox, and that&#39;s just not
right, because thought is a diphthong, and ox isn&#39;t meant to be.&lt;br&gt;
  &lt;br&gt;
I think I have on my hands an ox-ah merger, then an awe split, but I
had to write this post to work that out, so I may as well post it
anyways and then ask, does anyone have any insight?&lt;br&gt;
  &lt;br&gt;
